Graphical abstract Highlights ► A new mesoporous silica supported Pd (II) catalyst had been successfully prepared. ► The catalyst showed high activity for Suzuki coupling reaction. ► The catalyst was easily recovered by simple filtration. ► The catalyst was reused for five cycles without evident loss in activity. A new functionalized SBA-16 catalyst immobilized palladium (II) has been synthesized. Inductively coupled plasma (ICP), small-angle X-ray diffraction (XRD), transmission electron microscopy (TEM), nitrogen physical adsorption and Fourier transform infrared (FTIR) studies have been used to characterize the catalyst. The catalyst exhibited very high activity for Suzuki coupling reaction of aryl halides with arylboronic acids in EtOH/water under air atmosphere. On the other hand, the synthesized catalyst could be separated from the reaction mixture by simple filtration and reused up to five runs without significant loss in activity. Keywords Palladium Heterogeneous catalyst Schiff-base SBA-16 Suzuki reaction 1 Introduction Palladium is the most versatile and widely applied metal for the catalysis of various carbon–carbon bond forming reactions. Of these reactions, the palladium-catalyzed Suzuki cross-coupling reaction has become an extremely powerful synthetic method for preparing biaryl compounds, which constitute a wide range of natural products, agrochemicals, pharmaceuticals, and advanced materials [1–6]. The organoboronic acids commonly employed in the Suzuki reaction, which are nontoxic and thermally, air-, and moisture-stable. Typically, the reaction is catalyzed by soluble palladium complexes including different phosphorous or nitrogen-based as well as ligand-free palladium [7–10]. Although homogeneous catalysts frequently exhibit very high activity, the drawbacks of these catalysts are apparent. For example, homogeneous palladium catalysts are usually not reusable and the products are frequently contaminated by residual palladium or ligands [11]. To overcome these problems, it is highly desirable to develop new efficient and recyclable heterogeneous catalysts for Suzuki reaction. Therefore, the heterogenization of palladium catalyst is a promising option [12,13]. In recent years, many reports have appeared on Suzuki coupling catalyzed by supported palladium catalysts, which are loaded on activated carbon [14–16], zeolites and molecular sieves [17–20], diatomite [21], dendrimers [22,23], magnetic nanoparticles [24], mesoporous silica [25–27], polymeric microspheres, microcapsules and resin [28–30]. However, some heterogeneous palladium catalysts show lower reactivity than homogeneous ones due to leaching of palladium from the supports. In fact the leached palladium species is responsible for the catalytic activity in most of the cases [31–33]. Thus, there is a need to design of new heterogeneous catalysts that can retain the activities and selectivities of homogeneous catalysts. Now it is well known that the nature of supports plays a key role in palladium-based heterogeneous catalysis. Among different supports, mesoporous silica materials remain the most popular choice because of their relatively low cost, high thermal, mechanical stability and good catalytic performance [34]. SBA-15 and MCM-41 are the representative example for these types of materials and have been used as supports for palladium catalysts [35–37]. Recently, Molnar et al. [38] observed that palladium immobilized on silica modified with methyl or phenyl groups exhibited high activity and selectivity in the Heck reaction. So the choice of ligand for functionalization of mesoporous silica has an important effect on the catalytic activity and stability. In this context, nitrogen-containing ligands have received much attention owing to their ability to form various stable complexes with palladium, possible extended supramolecular systems and good properties. Dhara et al. [39] reported the palladium (II)–Schiff base complex anchored onto MCM-41 which showed high reactivity and recyclability for the Suzuki reaction. Compared with two-dimensional channel-like hexagonal mesoporous materials such as MCM-41 and SBA-15, SBA-16 has been found to be more attractive due to the three-dimensional cage-like mesoporous network (in which each spherical cage is connected with eight neighboring cages through entrances) [40,41]. Such a unique pore structure of SBA-16 has been proven to facilitate the fast diffusions of reaction molecules [42]. Considering that SBA-16 support has a three-dimensional cage-like pore structure and the catalytic palladium species is anchored onto the inner surface of the mesoporous material, we expect that SBA-16 supported palladium catalyst will exhibit high activity, stability and good reusability. Up to date, there exist a few reports on SBA-16 supported palladium catalysts that have been applied to the Suzuki reactions [27]. In this paper, we explore the synthesis (Scheme 1 ) of a new palladium(II) bound heterogeneous catalyst through functionalization of 3D-hexagonally ordered SBA-16 type material with 3-aminopropyltriethoxysilane followed by the grafting with 2-acetylpyridine. This functionalized mesoporous material acts as an effective palladium catalyst for the Suzuki reaction. 2 Experimental 2.1 Materials Pluronic P123 (EO20PO70EO20) and F127 (EO106PO70EO106) were purchased from Sigma–Aldrich. 3-Aminopropyltriethoxysilane was obtained from Alfa Aesar. PdCl2 (99%) and 2-acetylpyridine were obtained from Lanzhou Aihua Chemical Reagent Company. Arylboronic acids, aryl halides were purchased from Shanghai Chemical Reagent Company. Tetraethoxysilane and other reagents were obtained from Tianjin Guangfu Fine Chemical Research Institute. All solvents were of analytical grade and used without further purification. Deionized water was used in the present study. 2.2 Synthesis of SBA-16 Mesoporous material SBA-16 was synthesized according to the procedure described elsewhere [43,41]. A mixture of Pluronic F127 (1.484g) and P123 (0.238g) were used as the templates. The mixed templates were completely dissolved in a solution of 60mL of deionized water and 10.5g of concentrated hydrochloric acid (36%), the solution was magnetically stirred at 35°C for 4h. And then 5.6mL of tetraethylorthosilicate was added dropwise to the solution. After being magnetically stirred for 40min, the suspension was transferred into a Teflon autoclave. The autoclave was placed under static conditions at the same temperature for 24h. Subsequently, the temperature of the autoclave was raised up to 100°C and kept at that temperature for 32h. After the hydrothermal treatment, the precipitated solid was isolated by filtration, dried in air at room temperature, and yielding white powders. The products were calcined at 550°C for 10h to remove the templates. Thus, the final mesoporous silica material was obtained. 2.3 Preparation of the 3-APTES functionalized SBA-16 Mesoporous material (SBA-16) (1g) was added to a solution of 3-aminopropyltriethoxysilane (1.8g) in toluene (150mL) and refluxed for 24h under N2 atmosphere. The white solid was filtered and washed repeatedly with ethanol, and finally dried at 50°C under vacuum. 2.4 Grafting of 2-acetylpyridine on functionalized SBA-16 The 3-APTES functionalized SBA-16 (1g) was added to the solution of 2-acetylpyridine (1.0g) in methanol (25mL) at 60°C for 8h. The resulting solid was collected by filtration, repeatedly washed with ethanol to remove unreacted 2-acetylpyridine. It was dried at 50°C under vacuum. 2.5 Synthesis of the Pd (II)–SBA-16 catalyst The catalyst was prepared by stirring a mixture of modified mesoporous silica (1g) and palladium chloride (0.05g) in ethanol (50mL) at room temperature for 24h. After stirring, the catalyst was filtered, washed several times with ethanol and dried under vacuum at 50°C. 2.6 Catalytic Suzuki reactions In a typical procedure, aryl halide (0.5mmol), phenylboronic acid (0.75mmol),K2CO3 (1.0mmol), EtOH/H2O (v/v=9:1, 5.0mL) and catalyst (0.5mol% Pd) were added in a 10mL round bottom flask. The mixture was vigorously stirred at 80°C for required time under air atmosphere. After the completion of the reaction, the mixture was cooled to room temperature and filtered. The filtrate was extracted with ethyl acetate (2× 5mL). The combined extracts were dried with Na2SO4, filtered and analyzed by GC (P.E. AutoSystem XL) or GC–MS (Agilent 6890N/5973N). 2.7 Catalyst recycling in Suzuki reaction A mixture of aryl iodide (0.5mmol), phenylboronic acid (0.75mmol),K2CO3 (1.0mmol), EtOH/H2O (v/v=9:1, 5.0mL) and the catalyst (0.5mol% Pd) was stirred at 80°C under air atmosphere. At the end of reaction, the mixture was cooled to room temperature and filtered to obtain the palladium catalyst. The separated catalyst was washed with ethanol and dried under vacuum at 50°C. After this, it could be used for the next run. 2.8 Characterization The Pd content of catalyst was measured by inductively coupled plasma (ICP) on IRIS Advantage analyzer. Small-angle powder X-ray powder diffraction was performed on a Rigaku D/max-2400 diffractometer using Cu-Ka radiation as the X-ray source in the 2q range of 0.5–5°. The morphology and microstructure of the mesoporous material were observed by a Tecnai G2 F30 transmission electron microscopy and samples were obtained by placing a drop of a colloidal solution onto a copper grid and evaporating the solvent in air at room temperature. The BET surface area and pore-size distribution were obtained by measuring N2 adsorption isotherms at 77K by using a TriStar 3020 (Micromeritics). Fourier transform infrared spectra were collected on a Nicolet NEXUS 670 FTIR spectrometer with a DTGS detector, and samples were measured with KBr pellets. 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Catalyst preparation and characterization The immobilization of Pd (II) in chemically modified SBA-16 consists of the following steps as shown in Scheme 1. The content of Pd in the catalyst determined by inductive coupled plasma emission spectrometer (ICP) was 2.18wt%. The small-angle X-ray diffraction patterns of SBA-16 and the catalyst Pd (II)–SBA-16 are shown in Fig. 1 . The fresh SBA-16 shows a strong diffraction peak and two small diffraction peaks for the 110, 200 and 211 planes. All the peaks indicate SBA-16 has a well defined hexagonal symmetry and has long-range ordering of structure. Comparison of the diffraction patterns of Pd (II)–SBA-16 and SBA-16 indicates that the ordered cubic mesoporous structure of the material remains intact even after formation of the Pd complex in SBA-16 matrix. An overall decrease in the intensity of the peaks is observed after bound with Pd (II)–complex. This is attributed to the presence of guest moieties on the mesoporous framework of SBA-16, resulting in the decrease of crystallinity but not collapse of the pore structure of mesoporous materials [44]. Fig. 2 shows the TEM images of SBA-16, Pd (II)–SBA-16 and Pd (II)–SBA-16 after five runs. For fresh SBA-16 (Fig. 2a), the highly ordered arrangements of mesopores reveal that the material consists of a high-quality body-centered cubic mesostructure. In Fig. 2b, Pd (II)–SBA-16 presents a well-ordered mesopores structure characteristic of the SBA-16 material, which indicates that the mesostructure of SBA-16 can be substantially conserved after the grafting process. In order to obtain the structural information about the solid catalyst on a mesoscopic scale, the N2 sorption isotherms and pore size distribution plots for SBA-16 and Pd (II)–SBA-16 are displayed in Figs. 3 and 4 respectively. SBA-16 exhibits a type IV isotherm with a steep capillary condensation/evaporation step and a type H2 hysteresis loop, which is characteristic of the mesoporous cage-like structure. Similar to the parent SBA-16, Pd (II)–SBA-16 also shows a type-IV isotherm with an H2 hysteresis loop, indicating that the catalyst still maintains a good mesoporous cage-like structure. The BET surface area and pore volume of SBA-16 is 700m2g−1 and 0.64ccg−1, whereas for Pd (II)–SBA-16, this value decrease to 76m2g−1 and 0.10ccg−1, respectively. It is worthwhile to note that the surface area, pore volume and pore size of the Pd (II)–SBA-16 undergo a drastic reduction. During functionalization via 3-aminopropyltriethoxysilane and later grafting by the 2-acetylpyridine, the BET surface area decreased by 624m2g−1, which was close to the value of 798m2g−1 for a similarly prepared mesoporous catalyst by Dhara et al. [39]. This can be attributed to the more loading of organics, which occupy the void space inside the mesopores. Fig. 5 shows the FT-IR spectra of SBA-16 (a), 3-APTES-SBA-16 (b), Schiff base-SBA-16 (c), Pd (II)–SBA-16 (d) and Pd (II)–SBA-16 after five runs (e). The spectrum of parent SBA-16 exhibits a broad band at 1633cm−1 due to OH bending vibration. CH and NH vibration bands in the 3100–2800cm−1 and 1650–1500cm−1 regions are found in the IR spectra of the 3-APTES-SBA–16, and these bands are surely absent in SBA-16. Meanwhile, the intensity of the peak at 960cm−1 (related to the bending vibration of Si–OH on SBA-16) significantly decreases after grafting with 3-APTES. This result shows that 3-APTES has been attached into the SBA-16 matrix. Interestingly, after 2-acetylpyridine treatment, one change in the spectra has been noticed, the OH band at 1628cm−1 merges with a new broad band centered at 1640cm−1 attributable to the CN stretching of imine generated through Schiff base condensation between amine group of 3-APTES and carbonyl group of 2-acetylpyridine. Thus it is evident that the acetyl groups are converted into Schiff base. In Fig. 5(d), the CN stretching frequency is shifted to lower frequency (1632cm−1) indicate to form Pd complex. The stretching frequency at 576cm−1 in the spectrum of Pd (II)–SBA-16 indicates ν Pd–N [45]. 3.2 Catalytic Suzuki coupling reaction To test the catalytic activity of Pd (II)–SBA-16 in the Suzuki reaction, the reaction between iodobenzene and phenylboronic acid was chosen as model reaction using K2CO3 as base. Influences of different parameters were examined to obtain the best possible combination. The parameters included solvent, reaction temperature, catalyst concentration and the reaction period. As shown in Table 1 , the coupling reaction yields were susceptible to temperature changes in the presence of 0.5mol% catalyst and EtOH as solvent (entries 1–3). The increase of reaction temperature up to 80°C led to excellent yields (97%). After 2.5h heating, the good yields were given in the presence of 1.0mol% catalyst at 80°C (entry 5), when the loading of catalyst was decreased to 0.1mol%, the yield were observed to be very slow (entry 6). The effect of various solvents was next investigated. While protic solvents like EtOH or MeOH were used as solvent, almost quantitative product formation was obtained after 2.5h (entries 3 and 7), the aprotic solvents such as toluene, DMF gave low yields during the same time (entries 8 and 9). Interestingly, when H2O was used as the solvent only poor yield was obtained (entry 10). Comparing with these solvents, the organic/aqueous mixture as reaction solvent provided much better yields (entries 11 and 12). The merit of the co-solvent was attributed to the good solubility of the organic reactants and the inorganic base. Based on the reaction yields and environmental consideration, the EtOH/H2O (v/v=9:1) combination was the best solvent for Suzuki reaction. Therefore, the following condition was used for the Suzuki coupling: 0.5mol% of Pd (II)–SBA-16 catalyst, 1.0equiv. of K2CO3 in EtOH/H2O at a temperature of 80°C. Under the optimized reaction conditions, the scope of the reaction was explored with various aryl halides and arylboronic acids. As shown in Table 2 , the coupling of aryl iodides proceeded smoothly at 80°C and the corresponding products were obtained high yields (entries 1–5 and 11–15). We further investigated the catalytic activity for the coupling of aryl bromides, aryl bromides and their derivatives efficiently reacted with phenylboronic acid or 4-methylphenylboronic acid, to yield biphenyls in excellent yields (entries 6–10 and 16–20). It could be concluded that aryl iodides bearing an electron-donating or electron-withdrawing group were obtained excellent yields. Meanwhile, for aryl bromides with substituents such as COCH3, NH2 and NO2, moderate to high yields were achieved. However, the reaction of 4-bromotoluene was observed a moderate yield with relatively longer time (entries 7 and 17), this phenomenon was probably due to the electronic and steric effects of the substitutent. Usually, the electron-withdrawing substitutent is generally more active than the electron- donating substitutent (such as CH3). Although, aryl bromides and iodides were found to be very effective substrates, unfortunately, we prepared catalyst has failed to produce biaryl compounds when chlorobenzene was used as substrate (entry 21). The low reactivity of chlorides was resulted from the strength of the CCl bond, whose bond dissociation energy was 96kcal/mol [46]. Recently, Dhara et al. [39] investigated the immobilization of Pd (II) on amine-functionalized MCM-41 which showed high reactivity for the Suzuki reaction of aryl bromide. It was noteworthy that we prepared catalyst exhibited very high activity for Suzuki coupling reaction not only with aryl bromide but also with aryl iodide. Meanwhile, contrary to our environmentally friendly aqueous-alcoholic media under air atmosphere, the reported catalyst was used in DMF medium at higher temperature (100°C) under argon atmosphere and it has been established that leaching of Pd often occurs in CC coupling reaction if DMF is used as a solvent [47]. Moreover, the catalytic activity of the reported catalyst was significantly decreased after the second run, although a satisfactory yield was finally obtained with longer reaction time (10h) in the second run. Compared with their report, our catalyst showed excellent catalytic activity even after five times of recycling under the same reaction time. The recyclability of Pd (II)–SBA-16 was further studied because the recycling of the heterogeneous catalyst was an important issue for practical applications. The coupling reaction of iodobenzene with phenylboronic acid was chosen as the model reaction. As shown in Table 3 , the recovered catalyst was added to reaction mixture under the same conditions for five cycles without a significant loss of yield and catalytic activity. Metal leaching was studied by ICP analysis of the catalyst after the reaction. The Pd content (2.06wt%) of the recovered catalyst remained just about the same as the fresh catalyst, indicating that Pd leaching was negligible. Furthermore, the filtrate obtained from the filtration of the catalyst after catalysis did not exhibit any catalytic activity. As was shown in Fig. 5e, the FT-IR spectrum of Pd (II)–SBA-16 after five runs still kept the characteristic peaks compared with that of fresh catalyst. From the TEM images (Fig. 2c), it can be seen that the cage-like structure of the reused catalyst did not have an obvious change. The good reusability may be attributed to the isolated nanocages of SBA-16 which could efficiently prevent the aggregation of Pd particles formed during the catalytic reaction. 4 Conclusions In conclusion, a new mesoporous silica supported palladium (II) catalyst had been successfully prepared via sequential grafting of several organic molecules. The catalyst has shown high activity towards Suzuki coupling reaction. It could be easily recovered by simple filtration and a good yield was obtained even after the catalyst was reused five times. These advantages make this methodology attractive for the development of large-scale industrial synthesis. coredata.dc:description: A new functionalized SBA-16 catalyst immobilized palladium (II) has been synthesized. Inductively coupled plasma (ICP), small-angle X-ray diffraction (XRD), transmission electron microscopy (TEM), nitrogen physical adsorption and Fourier transform infrared (FTIR) studies have been used to characterize the catalyst. The catalyst exhibited very high activity for Suzuki coupling reaction of aryl halides with arylboronic acids in EtOH/water under air atmosphere. On the other hand, the synthesized catalyst could be separated from the reaction mixture by simple filtration and reused up to five runs without significant loss in activity.
